About:
Product and Background Product is an innovative website portal which allows restaurants individually, and as an industry, to sell their goods and services online. It is differentiated from competitors such as Open Table in the extent to which restaurants can monetize products and services, increase sales, and receive payments prior to delivering the goods & services. The patent-pending system built by restaurateurs for restaurateurs has been created to leverage technology and E-Commerce giving restaurant pros more time to focus on their hospitality and F&B output while being open 24/7. The software is loaded with a Suite of E-Products (4 in total), suggestive sales tools (to help increase each sale), industry-specific search filter icons, a simple two-prong loyalty program, a three-tiered advertising banner program: Product/Service to Restaurant; Product/Service to our Customers and Product/Service to Consumers or any combination thereof. System has been beta tested in-house, and by the end of this month we will be looking to beta test with a limited number of selected restaurants. Our long-term plan is to apply this technology (baptized W.I.S.E. Meaning Whole Industry Internet Sales Engine) to other industries such as the Health & Beauty Industry, Wineries, Bars/Night Clubs, Home/Interiors and Boutiques/Shopping amongst others. Founders Comments My background in entrepreneurship includes 30+ years in publishing guide books with a focus on Food & Beverage in the Bay Area and internationally, advertising sales in Food & Beverage Guides to NY, L.A. and Florida plus launching an international franchise system for the founders family of restaurants. Your vision, expertise and impressive team would be ideal for this project because great minds think alike. Great Product + Great Team = Success. I am ready whenever you are! Please call me: 415.407-5571.

We hold the key to the restaurant industrys ability to sell online like the travel industry does. Its no surprise that investment in food industry technology is skyrocketing: http://www.cbinsights.com/blog/venture-capital/food-technology. The National Restaurant Association Ops Report also concludes that restaurants are ready to embrace new media and capitalize on the Internet to increase their sales. The size of the industry in the U.S. $660.5 billion sales projected for 2013, and were ready to take it on.

Algorithms designed to solve mathematical problems were the reason I got involved in Computer Science as a freshman studying Mathematics and Mechanical Engineering five years ago; ever since, these have been the problems that have defined my professional and academic pursuits. The breadth and multidisciplinary nature of my subsequent experiences has given rise to many different applications (computational geometry and meshing, computational neuroscience, and computational mechanics/acoustics) in many different environments (internships at large simulation companies, appointments at university research groups, and a full time R&D position at US defense contractor). These experiences, however, have all been related by the common theme of combining Computer Science and rigorous mathematics to solve exciting computational problems. Now, holding a B.Sc. in Computer Science and Mechanical Engineering, I seek to extend this lineage of computational software development into the field of statistical learning (Machine Learning, Artificial Intelligence, et al) with a Master’s degree in Computer Science from Brown University; and though I have limited formal experience in this specific concentrations of Computer Science, the breadth and intensity of my general mathematical and computational preparation is evident – skills which are fundamentally requisite and correlated to success in the field of machine learning. Early in my undergraduate career, I began exerting substantial effort to the pursuit of computational and mathematical endeavors well beyond the requirement of my major, taking rigorous coursework in theoretic mathematics, simulation, and algorithms. The result of this was a high level of mathematical exposure, theoretical maturity, and perspective regarding the applications of my academic interests. This summarizes my experience at the University of North Dakota, and culminated in a year-long full-time appointment at the Pittsburgh-based simulation company ANSYS. This experience further refined and solidified my interests in mathematical applications in Computer Science, and inspired the last-minute addition of a major in Computer Science upon transferring to the University of Pittsburgh. These experiences had intensely refined my academic interests, and my time in Pittsburgh was spent working in computational and research capacities for 20-30 hours a week, in addition the coursework required to complete my two technical majors without delaying graduation. Assuredly, my GPA could have been improved by not perusing these time consuming endeavors, but I knew my interests and my priorities (for better or worse) were shifted accordingly.
